				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-41641cf elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-theme-post-title elementor-page-title elementor-widget=
-heading" data-id=3D"41641cf" data-element_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=
=3D"theme-post-title.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<h1 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">Yeast Sta=
rter Method</h1>				</div>
				</div>
				<div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-2c507b1 elementor-wid=
get__width-inherit text elementor-widget elementor-widget-theme-post-conten=
t" data-id=3D"2c507b1" data-element_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"the=
me-post-content.default">
				<div class=3D"elementor-widget-container">
					<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"></p><div style=3D"margin-left: auto;=
margin-right: auto;text-align: center;" id=3D"brulo-1220129782"><ins class=
=3D"adsbygoogle" style=3D"display: block; height: 280px;" data-ad-client=3D=
"ca-pub-9494311560972116" data-ad-slot=3D"8522443393" data-ad-format=3D"aut=
o" data-adsbygoogle-status=3D"done"><div id=3D"aswift_1_host" style=3D"bord=
er: none; height: 280px; width: 534px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position:=
 relative; visibility: visible; background-color: transparent; display: inl=
ine-block;"></div></ins>

</div><p></p>
<p>The first beers I made were fermented with&nbsp;liquid yeast, my process=
 looking something like this:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">1. Take yeast out of fridge a few hours b=
efore brewing<br>
2. Once wort was chilled to about 75=C2=B0F, open vial and pitch<br>
3. Place fermentor in closet and hope the airlock is bubbling the next day<=
/p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">While those first few beers were nothing&=
nbsp;spectacular, they still came out pretty damn good, at least to the poi=
nt I never dumped a batch. It wasn=E2=80=99t until I really got serious abo=
ut brewing at home that I even heard of yeast starters, which I initially v=
iewed as being more work than it was worth. After a couple batches that jus=
t didn=E2=80=99t come out the way I planned, I figured one of the more simp=
le things I could&nbsp;try was making a starter.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">I=E2=80=99ve never looked back.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">I fairly regularly field&nbsp;questions a=
bout whether making a starter is really all that necessary. My honest respo=
nse is always the same: no. The truth is, you can make a perfectly good bee=
r by pitching a single vial or pack of liquid yeast into wort. In fact, I r=
ecently heard from a dude who said he took 1st place in category with a bee=
r he didn=E2=80=99t use a starter on, which is fucking great! And I=E2=80=
=99m certain he=E2=80=99s not the only one with a similar story. So what=E2=
=80=99s the point? Why invest the time and money making yeast starters when=
 it is obviously possible to make a delicious beer without one?</p>
<div style=3D"margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto;text-align: center;" id=
=3D"brulo-3171564017"><ins class=3D"adsbygoogle" style=3D"display: block; h=
eight: 280px;" data-ad-client=3D"ca-pub-9494311560972116" data-ad-slot=3D"8=
522443393" data-ad-format=3D"auto" data-adsbygoogle-status=3D"done"><div id=
=3D"aswift_2_host" style=3D"border: none; height: 280px; width: 534px; marg=
in: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; visibility: visible; background-=
color: transparent; display: inline-block;"></div></ins>

</div>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Now, I=E2=80=99m no microbiologist. Not e=
ven close. I could pretend to know more than I do about budding and conjuga=
tion (thanks Wikipedia), but the simple fact of the matter is I=E2=80=99m h=
ugely ignorant when it comes to these issues. What I do know is that I love=
, in an almost lustful sort of way, what yeast does for beer. I=E2=80=99m f=
ascinated by the amazing plethora of flavors different types of yeast can c=
reate and how it acts differently depending on the environment. After hundr=
eds of batches, fermentation still seems like magic to me. I abide by the d=
octrine that <i>brewers make wort, yeast make beer.</i></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">While starters may not be necessary, they=
 absolutely serve a function. I=E2=80=99m not sure new brewers ought to str=
ess too much about this part of the process, at least in the beginning, tho=
ugh the investment is fairly minimal for what I believe to be a good payoff=
. Some of my main reasons&nbsp;for making yeast starters:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">=E2=80=93 Visibly observing yeast activit=
y in a starter provides me&nbsp;with assurance the yeast is viable and read=
y to go to work turning wort into beer.<br>
=E2=80=93 While in the starter, yeast go through&nbsp;a&nbsp;growth phase, =
meaning there are significantly more&nbsp;cells being pitched&nbsp;into my&=
nbsp;wort, leading to decreased lag and a quicker fermentation with less ch=
ance of off-flavor development.<br>
=E2=80=93 Pitching a starter has significantly increased the <em>consistenc=
y</em> of my brewing, making it much easier for me to replicate a batch.<br=
>
=E2=80=93 <a title=3D"Yeast Harvesting" href=3D"https://brulosophy.com/yeas=
t-harvesting/">Free yeast for future use</a>! How would I harvest clean yea=
st if I didn=E2=80=99t have a starter to steal it from?</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">I=E2=80=99m sure with very little searchi=
ng, numerous other reasons for making a starter can be found, along with mu=
ch more scientific sounding explanations why one should make them. My point=
 is this: in my brewing, making starters seems to have had one of the bigge=
st impacts on the quality and consistency of the beer I make.</p>
<div style=3D"margin-left: auto;margin-right: auto;text-align: center;" id=
=3D"brulo-2731139187"><ins class=3D"adsbygoogle" style=3D"display: block; h=
eight: 280px;" data-ad-client=3D"ca-pub-9494311560972116" data-ad-slot=3D"8=
522443393" data-ad-format=3D"auto" data-adsbygoogle-status=3D"done"><div id=
=3D"aswift_3_host" style=3D"border: none; height: 280px; width: 534px; marg=
in: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; visibility: visible; background-=
color: transparent; display: inline-block;"></div></ins>

</div>
<h2>How I Make Yeast Starters</h2>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">I see a lot of starter how-tos that diffe=
r from my process in various ways. With my penchant for simplification, I=
=E2=80=99ve settled on a method that seems to require a little less effort =
and has worked well over the years. The first step is determining the prope=
r starter size,&nbsp;which is a function of the OG of your wort,&nbsp;batch=
 size, and yeast age. <a href=3D"http://yeastcalculator.com/" target=3D"_bl=
ank" rel=3D"noopener">Yeast Calculator</a> is my calculator of choice. All =
you have to do is plug in the aforementioned data, select a =E2=80=9Cmethod=
 of aeration,=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99ll spit out the details. Easy-peezy. =
Just remember to a make a larger starter&nbsp;if you plan to <a title=3D"Ye=
ast Harvesting" href=3D"https://brulosophy.com/yeast-harvesting/" target=3D=
"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">harvest yeast for future</a> use!</p>
<p><a href=3D"http://yeastcalculator.com/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopene=
r"><img fetchpriority=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter size=
-large wp-image-1341" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014=
/08/zz-yc.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"zz-YC" width=3D"620" height=3D"469"></a></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Yeast starters require little in the way =
of equipment, of which there are many options.&nbsp;I personally&nbsp;prefe=
r using <a href=3D"http://morebeer.com/products/erlenmeyer-flask-5000-ml.ht=
ml?a_aid=3Dbrulosophy" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">5 liter Erlenmeye=
r flasks</a> for myriad reasons, such as the ability to make larger starter=
s for lager beers and larger batch sizes.&nbsp;I also have a&nbsp;<a href=
=3D"http://morebeer.com/products/erlenmeyer-flask-2000-ml.html?a_aid=3Dbrul=
osophy" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">2 L flask</a>&nbsp;I occasionall=
y use for smaller batches of beer. I=E2=80=99m a huge fan of &nbsp;<a href=
=3D"http://www.homebrewing.org/The-Stirstarter-Yeast-Stir-Plate-_p_1306.htm=
l?AffID=3D368" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">StirStarter stir plates</=
a>&nbsp;due to their very affordable price-point, durability, and lifetime =
warranty (they make&nbsp;a <a href=3D"http://www.homebrewing.org/The-Stirst=
arter-Yeast-Stir-Plate-5L_p_3329.html?AffID=3D368" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener">new larger model</a> now as well). While not really a piece of e=
quipment,&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://morebeer.com/products/foam-control-fermcap=
s-1-oz.html?a_aid=3Dbrulosophy" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">FermCap-=
S</a>&nbsp;(anti-boilover agent)&nbsp;is an absolutely necessary part of my=
 yeast starter kit that has saved me from more volcanic eruptions (and clea=
n-ups) than I can count. That=E2=80=99s about it. For those who aren=E2=80=
=99t ready to invest in a fancy flask and stir plate, a clean and sanitized=
 growler shaken every time you walk by will get you by. If you=E2=80=99re g=
ood with electronics and have the desire, you might also consider building =
your own stir plate.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Weigh out <a hre=
f=3D"http://morebeer.com/products/dried-malt-extract-dme-light.html?a_aid=
=3Dbrulosophy" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">DME</a> and add it to you=
r clean flask (a funnel helps)</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncen=
ter size-large wp-image-1342" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/2014/08/01_dmeinflask.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"01_dmeinflask" width=3D"620" =
height=3D"465"><br>
<strong>Step 2:</strong> Add&nbsp;<em>hot</em><strong><em>&nbsp;</em></stro=
ng>tap water from the faucet (if good quality, otherwise use cold), swirlin=
g the flask at first to fully incorporate the DME</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncen=
ter size-large wp-image-1343" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com/wp-content/uplo=
ads/2014/08/02_addh2o.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"02_addh2o" width=3D"620" height=
=3D"465"><br>
<strong>Step 3:</strong> Once proper amount of water is added (I usually go=
 a hair over my target to account for boiloff), swirl a bit more to make su=
re there is no DME stuck to the bottom of the flask, then add a couple drop=
s of <a href=3D"http://morebeer.com/products/foam-control-fermcaps-1-oz.htm=
l?a_aid=3Dbrulosophy" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">FermCap-S</a></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" =
class=3D"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1344" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com=
/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/03_fermcaps.jpg" alt=3D"03_fermcapS" width=3D"4=
80" height=3D"640"><br>
<strong>Step 4:</strong>&nbsp;Place flask on stove, turn burner to high</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" =
class=3D"aligncenter size-full wp-image-1345" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com=
/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/04_stove.jpg" alt=3D"04_stove" width=3D"480" he=
ight=3D"640"><br>
<strong>Step 5:&nbsp;</strong>Watch the flask and turn burner down to low-m=
ed once bubbles start rising from the bottom of the flask.<br>
<strong>Step 6:</strong> Once wort is boiling, set timer for 10 minutes, an=
d watch for potential eruptions! A quick blow down the shaft of the flask w=
ill kill any large bubbles that may form.<br>
<strong>Step 7:</strong> While wort is boiling, make a small bowl of saniti=
zer solution for the foil and stir bar</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" =
class=3D"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1346" src=3D"https://brulosophy.co=
m/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/05_sanitizefoilstirbar.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"05_=
sanitizefoilstirbar" width=3D"620" height=3D"465"><br>
<strong>Step 8:</strong>&nbsp;When the timer goes off,&nbsp;<em>carefully <=
/em>move the flask&nbsp;(<a href=3D"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000VS=
63DE/ref=3Das_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=3DUTF8&amp;camp=3D1789&amp;creative=3D=
9325&amp;creativeASIN=3DB000VS63DE&amp;linkCode=3Das2&amp;tag=3Dbrulosophy-=
20&amp;linkId=3DNMCZZH2KZNRCOTQ6" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">OveGlo=
ves</a> are a godsend) to a sink with the drain plug in place, drop sanitiz=
ed stir bar in, cover top with sanitized foil,&nbsp;then&nbsp;surround it w=
ith ice and cold water.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" =
class=3D"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1338" src=3D"https://brulosophy.co=
m/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/08_chill.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"08_chill" width=
=3D"620" height=3D"465"><br>
<strong>Step 9:</strong> Once wort is chilled to about 70=C2=B0F, pitch roo=
m temperature yeast,&nbsp;set the flask on the stir plate, and get things s=
pinning.</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter size-large=
 wp-image-928" src=3D"https://brulosophy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/02_=
starters_1.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"02_starters_1" width=3D"620" height=3D"465">=
</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><strong>Step 10:</strong>&nbsp;About 36 h=
ours later, after stealing some yeast for future use, I usually move the fl=
ask to the fridge to crash overnight so I can decant the beer off before pi=
tching. Don=E2=80=99t forget to attach&nbsp;the stir bar to&nbsp;the side o=
f the flask with a strong magnet before crashing.</p>
<figure id=3D"attachment_1340" aria-describedby=3D"caption-attachment-1340"=
 style=3D"width: 620px" class=3D"wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading=3D"la=
zy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"size-large wp-image-1340" src=3D"https://br=
ulosophy.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/10_harvest.jpg?w=3D620" alt=3D"Free=
 yeast!" width=3D"620" height=3D"620"><figcaption id=3D"caption-attachment-=
1340" class=3D"wp-caption-text">Free yeast!</figcaption></figure>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">In the end, starters may not be totally n=
ecessary for beer production, though I think most experienced homebrewers w=
ould agree that it is one of the easiest ways to improve beer quality and c=
onsistency. If you=E2=80=99re looking to step up your game, I strongly enco=
urage you to consider making a starter for your next brew.</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Cheers!</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">***I=E2=80=99ve been asked a couple times=
 about how I decant the starter prior to using them. Basically, just gently=
 pour off all but maybe 500mL of starter beer, swirl up the rest to ensure =
homogeneity, then pitch as usual. If you have any other questions, don=E2=
=80=99t hesitate to ask!***</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><em><strong>ATTENTION:</strong></em><em> =
There is some concern Erlenmeyer flasks run the risk of shattering if&nbsp;=
placed directly on stove-top burners, particularly electric coils. If you s=
hare this concern or have small children around, you might consider boiling=
 your wort in a pot before adding it to your&nbsp;<span style=3D"text-decor=
ation: underline;">sanitized</span> flask.&nbsp;</em></p>
