							<section class=3D"ast-comment-content comment  entry-content">
								<p>Thanks for the great website guys.  It=E2=80=99s great to see so=
meone testing the many self perpetuating =E2=80=9Ctheories=E2=80=9D which g=
race typical homebrew forums.</p>
<p>I have a question about making yeast starters that, despite many hours s=
pent in various forums, I have not been able to find a scientific and repea=
table answer to.</p>
<p>When using a stir plate, how does one tell when the yeast have consumed =
all available sugars?</p>
<p>I put my first starter on a few days ago, which was Wyeast 1214.  It got=
 off to a really slow start, but eventually got going after about 48 hours =
(I tested with a refractometer after 48 hours and confirmed the OG was stil=
l at 1.040).  After another 12 hours or so, the liquid got really milky loo=
king, which I assume is a good sign of lots more yeast in suspension.  I th=
ough to myself I=E2=80=99ll give it another 48 hours then take another read=
ing to see where it=E2=80=99s at, but didn=E2=80=99t factor in the difficul=
ty of getting a good clear reading with fermented wort with lots of yeast i=
n the sample.  So it=E2=80=99s a bit hard to tell with an SG sample.  Obvio=
usly I=E2=80=99m not too keen on taking multiple large hydrometer samples i=
n such a small total volume.</p>
<p>So I wonder how a logical brain like yours approaches this situation whe=
n thing don=E2=80=99t quite start well.  Using the standard =E2=80=9Cjust w=
ait 24-36 hours=E2=80=9D doesn=E2=80=99t work if it takes the starter 48 ho=
urs to get going.  I feel like 48 hours after it visible kicks off might be=
 a good thumb in the air, but I=E2=80=99m looking for something more reliab=
le than that in case it=E2=80=99s just going slowly.  Having the starter on=
 a stir plate means the yeast is always in suspension, so I can=E2=80=99t t=
ell when it=E2=80=99s going dormant and dropping out.</p>
<p>Sorry for the long post.  Hopefully you or someone else has had these th=
ought and can contribute.  I=E2=80=99m probably just over thinking it, and =
it will all make more sense after I=E2=80=99ve done a few.</p>
<p>By the way, I=E2=80=99m following your yeast harvesting method, so I=E2=
=80=99m overbuilding this batch.  Which brings me to another question=E2=80=
=A6 what size are those Mason jars you use for yeast storage?</p>
<p>Thanks again for the website.  I don=E2=80=99t drink or make enough beer=
 myself to be able to experiment as much as I=E2=80=99d like to.  I brew vi=
cariously through this site so that the brews I actually do are better <img=
 draggable=3D"false" role=3D"img" class=3D"emoji" alt=3D"=F0=9F=99=82" src=
=3D"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/17.0.2/svg/1f642.svg"></p>
